{{Infobox member of the Knesset |image = Fares Hamdan.jpg |birth_date = 1910 |birth_place = {{nowrap|[[Baqa al-Gharbiyye]], [[Ottoman Empire]]}} |death_date = 29 November 1966 |death_place = |Knesset(s) = [[Israeli legislative election, 1951|2]], [[Israeli legislative election, 1955|3]] |party1 = [[Agriculture and Development]] |partyyears1 = 1951–1959 }}
'''Faras Hamdan''' ({{lang-ar|فارس حمدان}}; {{lang-he|פארס חמדאן}}, born 1910, died 29 November 1966) was an [[Israeli Arab]] politician who served as a member of the [[Knesset]] for [[Agriculture and Development]] between 1951 and 1959.
==Biography== Hamdan was born in [[Baqa al-Gharbiyye]] during the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman era]]. In 1944 he was elected head of local council of his village, where he later established a citrus confectionery factory.<ref>[https://www.knesset.gov.il/mk/eng/mk_eng.asp?mk_individual_id_t=420 Faras Hamdan: Public Activities] Knesset website</ref>
In [[Israeli legislative election, 1951|1951]] he was elected to the Knesset as head of the Agriculture and Development list, which was associated with the ruling [[Mapai]] party. The party joined [[David Ben-Gurion]]'s government, but Hamdan did not receive a ministerial portfolio.
He was re-elected in [[Israeli legislative election, 1955|1955]], and again joined the governing coalition. For the [[Israeli legislative election, 1959|1959 elections]] the party was headed by [[Mahmud A-Nashaf]]. It won only one seat and Hamdan lost his place in the Knesset.
He died in 1966.
